-- Module 10, Lesson 2: Freelancing vs. Agency vs. In-House
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Freelancing vs. Agency vs. In-House</h2><h3>Choosing Your Career Path</h3><p>Facebook Ads professionals have multiple career path options. Freelancing, agency work, and in-house positions each offer unique advantages and challenges. Understanding these differences helps you choose the path aligned with your goals and preferences.</p><h3>Freelancing Overview</h3><p>Independent contractor. Multiple clients. Flexible schedule. Location independence. Full business ownership. Highest income potential. Most autonomy. Requires self-discipline.</p><h3>Freelancing Advantages</h3><p>Flexibility and freedom. Choose clients and projects. Unlimited income potential. Diverse experience. Work from anywhere. Be your own boss. Significant upside.</p><h3>Freelancing Challenges</h3><p>Income inconsistency. Client acquisition responsibility. No benefits or stability. Isolation. Administrative burden. Feast or famine cycles. Self-motivation required.</p><h3>Agency Work Overview</h3><p>Employment at marketing agency. Multiple client accounts. Team environment. Structured career path. Steady income. Learning opportunities. Collaborative work.</p><h3>Agency Advantages</h3><p>Stable income and benefits. Team support and learning. Diverse client exposure. Career progression. Resources and tools. Mentorship. Professional development.</p><h3>Agency Challenges</h3><p>Long hours common. Client demands. Limited autonomy. Income ceiling. Office politics. Burnout risk. Less flexibility.</p><h3>In-House Overview</h3><p>Employee of single company. Focus on one brand. Deep expertise. Stable environment. Benefits and security. Work-life balance. Strategic involvement.</p><h3>In-House Advantages</h3><p>Job security and benefits. Work-life balance. Deep brand knowledge. Strategic impact. Team collaboration. Predictable schedule. Less client stress.</p><h3>In-House Challenges</h3><p>Limited scope and variety. Slower career growth. Income limitations. Less diverse experience. Potential boredom. Corporate constraints. Narrow focus.</p><h3>Income Comparison</h3><p>Freelance: $50-200+/hour, variable. Agency: $40-120K salary, bonuses. In-house: $50-150K salary, benefits. Freelance highest potential, most variable. Each has trade-offs.</p><h3>Lifestyle Considerations</h3><p>Freelance: Maximum flexibility, uncertainty. Agency: Demanding, social. In-house: Balanced, stable. Choose based on lifestyle preferences. No right answer.</p><h3>Career Development</h3><p>Freelance: Self-directed learning. Agency: Structured training. In-house: Company-specific growth. Each offers development opportunities. Different paths.</p><h3>Transitioning Between Paths</h3><p>Common to switch paths. Agency to freelance popular. In-house to agency for growth. Freelance to in-house for stability. Flexibility to change.</p><h3>Hybrid Approaches</h3><p>Part-time freelance + in-house. Agency + side clients. Multiple income streams. Risk mitigation. Flexibility. Test before full commitment.</p><h3>Decision Framework</h3><p>Income needs and goals. Lifestyle preferences. Risk tolerance. Learning style. Career aspirations. Personal values. Honest self-assessment guides choice.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Three main paths: freelancing, agency, in-house</li><li>Freelancing offers flexibility and income potential with uncertainty</li><li>Agency provides learning, team, steady income with demands</li><li>In-house offers stability, balance, focus with limited scope</li><li>Income potential varies: freelance highest but variable</li><li>Choose based on lifestyle, goals, risk tolerance</li><li>Transitioning between paths common and possible</li><li>Hybrid approaches offer flexibility and risk mitigation</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Meta Blueprint Certification Prep.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Freelancing vs. Agency vs. In-House' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

